<HL>
   Honda Creates Unit
   To Sell Cars in Italy
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A
</SO>
<CO>
   HMC
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Honda Motor Co. established a wholly owned
automobile importing and sales subsidiary in Verona, Italy,
scheduled to begin operations in October.
   To be called Honda Automobili Italia S.p.A., the unit was
capitalized at 43 billion lire ($36.9 million). The new
subsidiary will handle and reinforce automobile operations
previously managed by Honda Italia Industriale S.p.A., which
also manages motorcycle manufacturing and sales, as well as
power-product importing and sales.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Honda said that Italy's automobile market, with 2.362
million passenger vehicles sold in 1989, is the
second-largest in Europe next to West Germany. Not including
off-road, four-wheel drive vehicles, Japanese passenger
vehicles account for 8,579 units of this total, Honda said.
   Italy's market has grown at a 45% pace over the past five
years, the Japanese auto maker said.
   Honda Automobili Italia is expected to sell 4,500 units in
1990, including projected sales of 2,900 units through
September by the former sales office, the parent company
said. Sales are seen at 7,500 units in 1991.
   There is an import restriction for Japanese vehicles in
Italy, so Honda has been selling its automobiles through
licensed import. Italian sales of its Concerto model began in
April. The Concerto is produced by U.K. auto maker Rover
Group, a unit of British Aerospace PLC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900810-0137
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900810-0137.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   GM Output Hurt
   By Michigan Strike,
   Kuwait Invasion
   ----
   By Krystal Miller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   GM LABOR MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- Iraq's invasion of Kuwait and a strike by
workers in Flint, Mich., are forcing General Motors Corp. to
halt production at two of its U.S. assembly plants.
   GM said it will have to idle its car plant in Ypsilanti,
Mich., and lay off 4,200 workers for two weeks beginning Aug.
13 because the Gulf conflict has derailed an order for
Chevrolet Caprices and Buick Estate Wagons.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait is one of the best overseas markets for North
American-made GM cars. Kuwaitis particularly liked big,
full-sized GM sedans such as the Caprice. The auto maker had
two dealerships in Kuwait that sold about 10,000 GM vehicles
in 1989, most of them built in North America. GM sold a total
of about 40,000 vehicles in the entire Mideast region last
year.
   Earlier this week, GM said it was suspending work on
contracts with Iraq's State Enterprise for Automotive
Industry under which the auto maker was to have helped the
Iraqis build a plant that would assemble North American
designed GM cars and trucks.
   Separately, GM began to feel the effects of a strike at a
key parts-making facility in Flint. The auto maker yesterday
idled its truck plant in Moraine, Ohio, that builds sport
utility vehicles, putting 2,500 workers on lay-off.
   GM may have to idle as many as two more plants today
because they've run out of parts supplied by the Flint
operation, a company spokesman said. He declined to identify
which plants could be affected. GM has said as many as eight
of its North American assembly factories could be idled
within the next few days if the Flint walkout isn't resolved.
   Negotiations to settle the strike continued yesterday, but
without any apparent movement. "There hasn't been anything
serious to discuss," a top UAW official said yesterday. Talks
are scheduled to continue today.
</TEXT>
