</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Lever Brothers Will Bottle
   Liquids in Recycled Plastic
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   UN UL
</CO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Lever Brothers Co. said it has agreed to use
10 million pounds of recycled plastic annually in its bottles
for such liquid household products as Wisk laundry detergent
and Snuggle fabric softener.
   Lever Brothers has agreed to purchase 50% of the output of
a new plastics recycling facility owned by Sonoco Graham Co.,
one of the nation's largest producers of the type of
high-density plastics used in the bottles. The Sonoco Graham
recycling facility, in York, Pa., is scheduled to start
producing the resins in September.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Lever, a unit of Unilever Group, an Anglo-Dutch consumer
products company, in June began filling bottles that contain
some recycled resins. The new agreement with Sonoco Graham
will accelerate those efforts. By mid-1991, the company
predicts 50% of all its bottles will contain between 25% and
35% recycled plastic.
   Environmentalists have applauded these efforts. Said Sam
Hartwell, a research associate at the Natural Resources
Defense Council, "Creating demand for recovered materials is
an important step in encouraging consumers and municipalities
to recycle."
   But with consumers' interest in environmental protection
soaring, competitive pressures also play a big role. Procter
&amp; Gamble Co. already has announced plans to package liquid
laundry detergents in bottles made partly from recycled
plastic. Colgate-Palmolive Co. also plans to use recycled
plastics in bottles of dishwashing liquids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900810-0069
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900810-0069.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   California Hospital Group
   Sues State Health Agency
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A
</SO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   California's largest hospital association sued the state's
health department director, alleging that "woefully
inadequate" state Medi-Cal outpatient reimbursements violate
federal laws and cripple health care to the poor.
   Medi-Cal funds are matched by federal Medicaid dollars to
provide health care to 3.4 million eligible Californians.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The California Association of Hospitals and Health Systems
and the Orthopaedic Hospital in Los Angeles filed a lawsuit
against Ken Kizer, director of the State Department of Health
Service, in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. The
association says that outpatient service payments average 55
cents for every dollar hospitals spend to provide the care.
"Hospitals are getting clobbered with these rates," said C.
Duane Dauner, president of the association.
   A spokesman for the state health department declined to
immediately comment on the lawsuit.
   Mr. Dauner said California hospitals lose more than
$575,000 a day providing outpatient services to Medi-Cal
patients. He also said that since 1982, the state has
increased payment rates to hospitals for Medi-Cal outpatients
by 2%, while hospital costs have risen 50%. Similar lawsuits
in four states have resulted in higher payment rates to
hospitals, he said.
</TEXT>
