<HL>
   Business Brief -- Nordstrom Inc.:
   Retailer's Costs Rose, Profit
   Fell 7% in Second Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NOBE
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
</IN>
<LP>
   Nordstrom Inc., still grappling with rising costs,
reported profit fell 7% in the second quarter.
   Earnings for the second period, ended July 31, were off 7%
to $35.9 million, or 44 cents a share, from $38.5 million, or
47 cents in the comparable period last year. Costs and
expenses totaled $745.6 million, up nearly 12%, while sales
rose 10% to $801.8 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   John A. Goesling, the Seattle retailer's senior vice
president, said the company isn't "yet satisfied" with its
results. He added, however, that trends in sales and expenses
are "moving in the right direction." Sales increased at a
higher rate and expenses at a lower rate during the second
quarter than the first, ended April 30.
   Mr. Goesling said the company brought its inventories in
line with sales in the second quarter. It also took steps to
cut expenses across the board.
   Profits for the six months, ended July 31, declined 20% to
$49.1 million, or 60 cents a share, from $61.5 million, or 75
cents a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
