<DOCID>
900810-0018.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE STRATEGIC OIL RESERVE won't be drawn down for now, the
White House said, surprising some petroleum experts. World
crude prices fell about 25 cents a barrel, and several more
companies said they were cutting gasoline prices. The stock
and bond markets, meanwhile, rallied as bargain hunters
stepped in to buy. Bond prices gained about 3/4 point. The
Dow Jones industrials advanced 24.01 points to 2758.91.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Gillett Holdings missed a bond interest payment and is
trying to restructure the broadcasting and resort company's
$983 million in debt.
   ---
   Thrift regulators are seeking $40.9 million in restitution
from American Continental's Charles Keating, plus his removal
from the Lincoln S&amp;L parent. The sum is a fraction of the
$2.5 billion cost of Lincoln's failure.
   ---
   Heinz gave its chairman, Anthony O'Reilly, options to buy
four million shares of the food giant as part of a lucrative
contract that rewards him for consistently strong profits.
   ---
   Chrysler is postponing work on a new luxury car and
instead will focus on developing new midsized models
desperately needed by the car maker. The change reflects
weakness in the middle of the car maker's product line. st
   ---
   An alleged insider-trading ring that got information from
a Skadden Arps takeover lawyer is the target of federal civil
and criminal charges.
   ---
   Continental Air will achieve consistent profitability at
some point, predicted Hollis Harris, who succeeded Frank
Lorenzo as chief executive. Lorenzo's departure boosted the
carrier's share price $1.75 to $6.25.
   ---
   Retailers reported lackluster sales gains for July as
consumer demand continued to soften. The increases largely
fell in the range of 2% to 8%.
   ---
   Merrill Lynch quit work on restructuring $1.3 billion of
Trump's bond debt, people close to him say.
   ---
   General Motors is halting production at two U.S. assembly
plants because of the Mideast crisis and a strike at a GM
parts-making factory.
   ---
   Schering-Plough withdrew a new blood pressure drug from
distribution after 17 patients using the medication developed
liver complications.
   ---
   Procter &amp; Gamble's profit soared 66% in the quarter ended
June 30, reflecting strength in the company's detergent and
diaper products.
   ---
   Salomon plans to shrink its struggling Philipp Brothers
commodities unit at a cost of up to $200 million.
   ---
   The Big Board's new chairman, William Donaldson, said the
exchange must cut costs. The Donaldson Lufkin founder
succeeded John Phelan.
   ---
   The Agriculture Department forecast robust corn and wheat
production this year but lagging soybean output.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 155,810,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2758.91, off 24.01; transportation 998.18, up 6.76; utilities
204.48, off 1.07.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3385.20, up
24.73.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.67, up 0.22; spot
index 131.88, up 0.17.
   Dollar: 149.80 yen, up 0.65; 1.5965 marks, off 0.0040.
