<HL>
   Mideast Crisis
   May Cost U.S.
   Extra $3 Billion
   ----
   By Andy Pasztor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The confrontation in the Middle East could
cost the Pentagon $3 billion or more in unexpected costs for
fuel, spare parts and hazardous pay for troops if it
continues for several months, according to military budget
experts.
   The $3 billion estimate doesn't factor in possible damage
to U.S. ships and planes or the cost of ammunition and
missiles if actual fighting occurs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The largest part of the anticipated extra costs, according
to Pentagon officials and congressional aides, involves
higher fuel prices the military must pay world-wide as a
result of increases in the price of crude oil. The jump in
crude-oil prices after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait is likely to
mean nearly $2 billion in higher overall fuel costs for the
U.S. armed forces by early next year, according to some
internal Pentagon estimates.
   Unless world oil prices plummet -- which few people expect
-- those extra costs will strain Pentagon budget accounts
regardless of how long U.S. troops remain in Saudi Arabia.
   In addition, it's likely to cost hundreds of millions of
dollars to move large numbers of troops, planes and spare
parts to the Middle East, and then keep them there for an
extended period.
   The total price tag, of course, depends on the military
situation on the ground. But according to budget analysts,
the massive airlift and deployment of U.S. naval power in the
region entails huge extra fuel costs. Stepped-up air and sea
operations are bound to mean increased maintenance and
logistics costs.
   Neither the military nor congressional committees have
developed detailed cost estimates, and senior Pentagon
officials have declined to comment on the matter. But
officials note that the U.S. invasion of Panama earlier this
year -- a much simpler and smaller operation that lasted only
a few weeks -- cost the Defense Department nearly $400
million in extra operating and personnel costs.
   In the short term, each of the armed forces will try to
cope with the problem by cutting back on routine maintenance,
purchases and other nonessential operating expenses. But if
the military confrontation continues for several months, the
Pentagon either will have to ask Congress to approve a
supplemental appropriations measure or give it greater
authority to transfer funds among certain accounts.
   As part of that strategy, the White House announced
yesterday that President Bush plans to partly exempt spending
on military personnel from any automatic spending cuts that
might occur this fall.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Mr. Bush plans
to shield only as much Pentagon spending as needed to
maintain U.S. forces in Saudi Arabia. He said Mr. Bush and
his budget advisers, who conferred Wednesday night, still
aren't sure what the deployment will cost.
   Under the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law, Mr. Bush
must decide by Wednesday whether to exempt some or all
Pentagon spending on uniformed personnel from the automatic
spending cuts that will be triggered in October -- unless
Congress finds a way to reduce the deficit by $74 billion or
alters the Gramm-Rudman statute.
   Although the administration is preparing to impose about
$84 billion in Gramm-Rudman spending cuts, many in Congress
doubt cuts of that size will be allowed to go into effect
because they would be so disruptive to the government and
economy.
   If Pentagon personnel spending is protected, other
military spending would be cut more deeply under the law.
Should personnel be exempted entirely, Pentagon spending
would be cut by 34.9%, the White House budget office
estimated. Non-defense spending covered by the law would be
cut by 31.9%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900810-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900810-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Criminal Justice Is
   A Talk-Show Topic
   For Denny McLain
   ---
   Popular Detroit Radio Host
   And Former Tiger Pitcher
   Muses About Pete Rose
   ----
   By Neal Templin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<IN>
BIOGRAPHY (BIO)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- "It's time to slam-dunk the judge in Cincinnati
for putting Pete Rose in jail," says the Detroit radio talk
show host. "It serves no purpose whatsoever."
   That's the word from a man who has been there -- former
Detroit Tigers pitching ace Denny McLain, who served 2 1/2
years in federal prison before his conviction on charges of
racketeering, extortion and drug-dealing was overturned in
1987. He had been sentenced to 23 years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Rose, the former Cincinnati Reds player and manager,
entered the federal prison at Marion, Ill., this week to
serve five months for filing false income-tax returns. He was
also fined $50,000. As Mr. Rose begins his stint, he has
reason to take heart: If Denny McLain was able to make a
comeback, anybody probably can.
   In 1970, Mr. McLain was suspended from baseball three
times: first for investing in a bookmaking ring, then for
throwing water on sportswriters, and finally for carrying a
gun. Off the field, he lurched from one business disaster to
another, twice declaring insolvency.
   Life since prison has been kind to Mr. McLain, although at
46 years of age he is many pounds overweight and bears little
resemblance to the stylish athlete who in 1968 won 31 games
-- nobody since has come close -- and pitched the Tigers into
the World Series. But he has kept the crooked grin and
rough-spun sense of humor that amused Detroit baseball fans.
Even his love life has been aired on his show. He recently
told his listeners how "pure, unmitigated PMS" ruined an
anticipated romantic interlude with Mrs. McLain in a
heart-shaped Jacuzzi.
   "Of all the athletes I've known he is the most unusual,"
says Joe Falls, a Detroit News sports columnist, who has been
covering Mr. McLain since the early 1960s. "I like him," he
says, adding that he can't defend Mr. McLain's past behavior.
   Detroit likes him, too. His morning talk show at WXYT has
nearly doubled its ratings since Mr. McLain took over five
months ago. The show has 165,000 listeners, the station says.
Mr. McLain also appears on a local television sports show.
Outside Detroit, he gets paid for appearing at baseball-card
shows. He won't say how much he earns.
   As for Mr. Rose, Mr. McLain tells his radio audience,
"Money is the way to hurt Pete, not jail." He says the judge
should have fined Mr. Rose $500,000 instead of $50,000.
"While he's in jail," he says, "he'll line up a thousand card
shows."
   Mr. McLain -- himself a potential candidate for baseball's
Hall of Fame -- says Mr. Rose shouldn't be admitted to the
institution, at least if he did bet on baseball games, as the
late baseball commissioner A. Bartlett Giammatti alleged last
year. Mr. McLain says he himself limited his betting to other
sports.
   But even as a baseball player, Mr. McLain played by his
own rules. He once purposely served up a home-run pitch to
the aging Mickey Mantle. Between starts, he flew around the
country to speak, perform on the organ or hobnob with
celebrities. The Tigers' management tolerated his antics
because Mr. McLain kept winning. "He was a cocky s.o.b.,"
says Gates Brown, a Tiger teammate in those days. "Then
again, he had the reason to be."
   Mr. McLain's winning ways came to a screeching halt in
1970, the year he was suspended three times. When he did get
to play, his pitches had lost their zip. Mr. McLain's right
shoulder, which had been injected dozens of times with
cortisone shots, was worn out. Two years later, at the age of
28, he pitched his last major league game. By his own
account, Mr. McLain spent the next dozen years wheeling and
dealing.
   "It was like he was out there floundering about," says
Sharyn McLain, his wife of 27 years. "He did a lot of
different things, but nothing made him happy."
   The McLains spent most of their time in Florida, where Mr.
McLain eventually got into big trouble. By his own admission,
he was involved in gambling. A plane leased to him was used
to transport cocaine, although he denied knowing of any drug
shipment. Neither federal authorities nor a federal court
jury in Tampa believed his denials, and he was convicted.
   While Mr. McLain was behind bars, his family was forced to
sell the house, most of the furniture, and a car. His wife
and children took jobs. "One week we had spaghetti five
nights in a row, just getting less and less every night,"
Mrs. McLain recalls.
   After his release from prison in 1987, he pleaded guilty
to all the pending charges against him to avoid a retrial.
The judge in the case, however, said he had served enough
time in prison.
   Mr. McLain began making paid appearances at card shows and
doing public relations for a minor-league hockey team in Fort
Wayne, Ind. He played the keyboard at a Detroit area night
spot where Leon Spinks, the former heavyweight boxing
champion, tended bar. And, with Mike Nahrstedt of the
Sporting News, he wrote a book about his troubles entitled
"Strikeout: The Story of Denny McLain."
   Then he got a big break. WXYT, the Detroit radio station,
offered him a job in April 1989 after he appeared as a guest.
"When I first heard him on the air, I knew he had the gift of
gab," says Joan Cherry Isabella, the station's executive
producer.
   Mr. McLain worked afternoons for nearly a year. Then he
got his shot at the key morning rush-hour traffic slot from 6
a.m. to 9 a.m. weekdays.
   Mr. McLain lives in a rented house in an executive suburb
of Detroit. He drives his Chevrolet Blazer to the radio
station, showing up before 5 a.m. each day, with a 12-pack of
sodas under his arm, to begin leafing through newspapers. He
has always read newspapers voraciously and professes more
interest in city politics than in sports. "I never grabbed
the sports section first unless there was something negative
about me," he says.
   He takes a special interest in criminal justice and
regularly discusses local court decisions on the air. He
calls himself middle-of-the-road. He dislikes abortion, but
he is pro-choice. He is for gun control, the Equal Rights
Amendment and capital punishment. Sometimes he talks of his
own time in prison. Recently he had Arnold Levine, his former
defense attorney, as a guest.
   Ted Koppel he isn't. "He doesn't go for the throat," says
Ms. Isabella, "but a lot of people are willing to talk to him
because of that."
   In some ways, he is still the old Denny. When he played
baseball, he had a reputation for waving off signals from his
catcher and making the pitch he wanted. Now, he waves off
signals from his producer. "Denny makes the rules up as he
goes along," says the producer, Arthur Regner.
   Mr. McLain plays a game in which listeners answer
questions about newsmakers. Winners are supposed to get
symphony tickets. But on this occasion, Mr. McLain decides to
give out pizza coupons instead. The trouble is, the station
has run out of pizza coupons.
   "We occasionally have to run behind him with a little
mop," says Michael Packer, the station's vice president. But
the radio station is happy to do that as long as Mr. McLain
keeps pitching his audience-grabbing spiels.
   After the show, he attacks his usual breakfast (three
eggs, three sausage patties) at a nearby restaurant that he
calls the "House of Pain." He still walks with a ball
player's swagger, flinging open the door as he enters a room.
But his wife and friends say prison changed him -- for the
better. "Being there can humble a person," says Mr. Brown.
Before becoming a professional baseball player, Mr. Brown
spent two years in state prison in Ohio on charges of
breaking and entering.
   Prison will be an eye-opener for Mr. Rose, too, says Mr.
McLain. "When some guy comes up to him and says, `What's your
name?'" Mr. McLain muses, "That's what will shock him."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900810-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900810-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   U.S. Acts to Learn if Keating Has Millions
   For Restitution Months After S&amp;L Failed
   ----
   By Paulette Thomas
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   AMC
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A full 18 months after the costliest thrift
failure ever, federal savings-and-loan officials are trying
to learn whether the thrift's top executive, Charles Keating
Jr., has $40.9 million he can return to the failed S&amp;L.
   Under administrative proceedings begun yesterday, thrift
regulators are seeking an accounting of Mr. Keating's
finances as well as $40.9 million in restitution -- a
fraction of the $2.5 billion in losses stemming from the
failure of Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan Association.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The regulators also are seeking to remove Mr. Keating as
chairman of American Continental Corp., Lincoln's Phoenix,
Ariz., parent, along with five other officers. In addition,
the regulators also would require Mr. Keating to give them
two days' notice before transferring assets in excess of
$5,000.
   "We do not believe his statements to the press or to the
public that he is broke," said Timothy Ryan, the director of
the Office of Thrift Supervision. "There was too much money
that was available to him, and too short a time for it all to
disappear."
   The proceedings began on the first anniversary of the
savings-and-loan cleanup law and federal officials have been
putting the best face possible on the deteriorating mess in a
flurry of recent speeches and news briefings.
   "This action is literally bolting the barn door after the
horse left," says Robert Litan of the Brookings Institution,
a Washington think tank. "The money is already long gone.
This will join the many other cases in which they {the
regulators} may get successful judgments, but not any money."
   Lincoln, of Irvine, Calif., was seized by the government
in April 1989, one day after parent American Continental
filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the
U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   The amount of restitution is the largest ever sought by
the thrift office, Mr. Ryan said. He added that he didn't
believe that 18 months was a long spell before getting a
grasp of Mr. Keating's finances. "I think it's prompt
action," Mr. Ryan said, but he added: "I've only been here
four months." Previously, Mr. Ryan was an attorney at the
Labor Department.
   An American Continental spokesman, Brad Boland, who is Mr.
Keating's son-in-law, said that federal regulators are
explicitly familiar with Mr. Keating's finances through a
separate federal suit filed by the Resolution Trust Corp.
   "As usual, when they can't get the results they want in a
court of competent jurisdiction, they resort to
administrative fiat," he said, adding: "They know every
nickel he has." Mr. Boland said that Mr. Keating's extensive
legal bills are being paid through insurance companies.
   The administrative case is being pursued alongside a
tangle of several other suits between the government and Mr.
Keating, who has become a symbol of the high-flying thrift
executive investing in wild land schemes.
   American Continental is in the midst of bankruptcy court
proceedings in Phoenix. The company has sued the thrift
office in an effort to overturn its seizure of Lincoln.
American Continental bondholders have sued the company
alleging fraud. The Resolution Trust Corp. is in the midst of
a $1.1 billion civil racketeering lawsuit against Lincoln.
And a grand jury in Los Angeles also is investigating Lincoln
for possible criminal violations. Throughout all of these
proceedings Mr. Keating has consistently denied any
wrongdoing.
   The administrative case focuses on three transactions
involving Mr. Keating and several associates of American
Continental. Regulators contend that these transactions piled
up the $40.9 million of losses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900810-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900810-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S. Sees Strength
   In the Harvests
   Of Corn, Wheat
   ----
   By Albert R. Karr
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT (AGD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The government forecast robust corn and
wheat production but lagging soybean output, according to the
Agriculture Department's first full-scale crop estimates for
the year.
   The department forecast a 1990 corn harvest of 7.85
billion bushels, up 4% from last year's output and unchanged
from its July estimate. The department said that "excellent
growing conditions" last month offset late Corn Belt
plantings and dry weather in the Southwest.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Soybean production for this year was estimated at 1.84
billion bushels, down 5% from 1989 and 1% below the July
estimate, with soybean plantings off to a late start and
plant development continuing "behind normal," the department
said.
   These were the first field-survey forecasts for 1990 corn
and soybean production; previous estimates were based on
incomplete information, according to the department.
   The crop estimates, released after the close of futures
trading yesterday, were below those projected by many futures
analysts in recent weeks. With tighter-than-expected supplies
in the offing, soybean futures prices are expected to rise to
10 cents a bushel from five cents in early trading today on
the Chicago Board of Trade, analysts said.
   Corn futures prices may jump two to four cents a bushel
today in reaction to the government crop estimates, analysts
said.
   The figures released for the country's wheat crop aren't
expected to have as much of a market impact, analysts said.
   The corn estimate reflects good growing conditions, which
overcame wet weather earlier this year. Corn yields are
expected to average 117.7 bushels per acre, up 1.5 bushels
from last year but still below the record high of 119.4
bushels an acre in 1987. The department estimated that 1990
production of corn and other feed grains would be the highest
since 1986.
   It also forecast a sharp rise in wheat output to 2.71
billion bushels, up 33% from the drought-affected 1989 wheat
crop and slightly above the July estimate. Average yield was
estimated at 38.7 bushels an acre, 5.9 bushels more than in
1989, with output of wheat and other food grains expected to
be the largest since 1982. Winter wheat, the bulk of the
wheat crop, is nearly all harvested.
   With wheat stockpiles climbing, the department last week
said it would order a 10% to 20% cutback in 1991 wheat
acreage under the government-subsidized program. Wheat
surpluses fell sharply in recent years because the government
subsidized exports; the stockpiles this year are projected to
rise to 846 million bushels by June 1, 1991, from 535 million
bushels on June 1, 1989.
   The National Association of Wheat Growers blamed the
rising stockpiles on a recent decline in exports and the
department's cutback in spending on export subsidies
programs.
   Grain growers are expected to get less help from exports
than previously thought, according to a separate Agriculture
Department report released yesterday. The department's
forecast of Soviet Union grain imports for the marketing year
that began July 1 was reduced by six million tons to 30
million tons, the lowest level in four years. The latest
estimate would be down from 38 million tons in the previous
year.
   The department's forecast of 1990 Soviet grain production
was boosted by 15 million tons to 230 million tons, with
"bumper yields" cited. Both total Soviet grain production and
the wheat harvest were estimated at the highest levels since
1978, and the coarse-grain harvest was forecast at only
slightly below the 1987 level and two million tons under the
record high 1976 total.
   "World and U.S. wheat trade prospects have weakened,
mainly because of improved crops and reduced imports likely
for the Soviet Union and China," the department said.
</TEXT>
