<HL>
   Real Estate (A Special Report): Openers
   ---
   Notes on a Troubled Industry
</HL>
<DATE>
08/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE R5
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>

                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 400 commercial real-estate professionals were asked
to forecast annual real-estate appreciation through 1994. No
sector was predicted to even keep pace with inflation. The
main culprits: overbuilding, identified by nearly 90% as one
of the factors having the greatest impact on investment
performance, and economic recession, cited by 75%. Survey
respondents also named Houston as the single local market
with the most investment potential. The most overvalued
market: New York City.
   (Source: Ernst &amp; Young)
                                                                                                       

   Predicted Appreciation (1990-94)
                                                                                                       

   Apartment ..................................... 4.2%
   Warehouses .................................... 4.2%
   Central business district office .............. 3.2%
   Retail ........................................ 3.1%
   Suburban office ............................... 2.1%
   Consumer prices ............................... 4.8%
   ---
                      Boomers and Bust
                                                                                                       

   Demographics have clearly been on housing's side. No
longer. During the '70s and '80s, house-hungry baby boomers
pushed consruction -- and prices -- to astronomical levels.
The boomers are still hungry, and they're eager to shed their
old homes and buy new, bigger ones. There's only one problem:
The baby bust is coming up behind them, and there aren't
enough busters to buy the boomers' homes. That's going to put
a crimp on new-home construction. But the constructoin
industry isn't despairing entirely. If homeowners can't sell
and trade up, they do have an alternative: remodeling. The
National Association of Home Builders foreasts that by the
end of the decade, additions and alterations to existing
homes will rise to about one-third ofconstruction activity
from about one-fourth currently. "The trade-up is going to
happen," says David Seiders, chief economist of the home
builders' group. "It's just going to take a different form."
   (Source: Joint Center for Housing Studies, Harvard
University)
                                                                                                       

                          1980        1990        2000
                                   (projected) (projected)
                                                                                                       

 Total households
   (in millions)          81.1        94.1       105.6
                                                                                                       

 By age of head of household:
                                                                                                       

   65 and older           20%         22%         22%
   55-64                  16%         13%         14%
   45-54                  16%         15%         21%
   35-44                  17%         22%         23%
   25-34                  23%         22%         16%
   15-24                   8%          5%          4%
   ---
                      Let's Make a Deal
                                                                                                       

   So you love a good sale. The Resolution Trust Corp. has
just the thing for you] The government agency is trying to
unload its repossessed real estate -- more than 35,000
properties. You name it, the RTC probably has it. Here's a
random walk through some of those properties:
                                                                                                       

   -- Condominium shopping center, Perdido Key, Fla., 6.33
acres, next to beach, $1.8 million.
   -- The Burger Shoppe, Phoenix, Ariz., built in 1986,
$325,000.
   -- Former 444-unit ministorage complex, 4.6 acres,
Colorado Springs, Colo., $1.3 million.
   -- Auto-repair garage, Tampa, Fla., $220,000.
   -- Store, Hutchinson, Kan., unheated storefront, downtown,
poor condition, $15,000.
   -- Resort with golf course, 51 acres, Hilton Head, S.C.,
$1.7 million.
   -- Restaurant with barbecue pit, Artesia, N.M., built in
1982, $35,000.
   -- Church, New Iberia, La., in commercial area, built in
1965, $250,000.
   -- Residential development, 12.6 acres, Sarasota, Fla., 22
fully developed, 24 partially developed townhouse sites,
$600,000.
   -- Stucco house in Bakersfield, Calif., two bedrooms, one
bath, good condition, $50,000.
   -- Brick house, Tucson, two bedrooms, one bath, fair
condition, $26,950.
   -- Brick house, San Antonio, four bedrooms, 2.5 baths,
good condition, $61,900.
